<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission to DCMS Inquiry – Future of the BBC</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Graeme Thompson [FBB0051]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">From Graeme Thompson, Trustee of the Royal Television Society and Dean of Arts, Design and Media</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> University of Sunderland</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The North East of England </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">developed a substantial TV and production sector between the late 1960s and late 1990s as a result of significant investment in local production by ITV Tyne Tees and BBC North East. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Sadly </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">jobs and commissions started to dry up in the early part of the ne</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">w century as ITV pulled out of its studio complex in Newcastle and focused production on London. Ofcom meanwhile agreed with ITV that it could pull out of its </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">regional programme production licence commitment. Jobs were lost and many media professionals wer</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e forced to move to London to find work. The BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">maintained its commitment to regional production with current affairs/documentary productions Inside Out and The Politics Show. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">200</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> was a lowpoint for the region with the BBC’s decision to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">end its long ru</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">nning childrens</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> drama Byker Grove – which had been </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">a successful training ground for performers and production talent such as Ant &amp; Dec, Jill Halfpenny and Oscar winning director Tom Hooper. In the same year</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> ITV dropped </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">its own long running North East-</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">base</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">d drama Wire in the Blood.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It is to th</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e credit of the BBC, that executives</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> recognized the significance of the gap left by </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Byker Grove. Another childrens’</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> show was swiftly </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">parachuted into the region</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> The Revenge Files of Alistair </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Fury ran for just one seri</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">es and offered work to production staff who had </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">been </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">previously </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">employed on </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Byker Grove.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The new team at BBC North</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in Salford</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> – liaising with the local Royal Television Society and Northern Film and Media – decided </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">tap in to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the region’s expertise in c</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">hildrens’ pro</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">duction by moving Tracy Beaker R</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">eturns to Newcastle.  The decision was then taken to shift production of the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">60s detective drama Inspector George Gently from Ireland to Durham.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">CBBC quickly built on that momentum </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and brought new childrens’ d</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ramas Wolfblood and The Dumping Ground to the North East. They join the BBC1 period shopping drama The Paradise </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">(filmed near Sunderland) </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and ITV police </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">series Vera (filmed in Northumberland). The BBC invested more than £1m in creating sets at Lambton Castl</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e for The Paradise. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Northern Film and Media estimate these new television productions </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">contribute more than £6m to the production economy of the region</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> - £12,700 a day in salaries, accommodation and equipment hire.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Director of BBC North Peter Salmon said he believed the success of the BBC move to Salford would be judged not on its impact around the North West, but on its ability to engage</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> audiences and revive and develop programme teams in Yorkshire and the North Eas</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">t.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The current level of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">television </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">pro</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">duction </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in the North East proves </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the BBC is taking that strategy seriously. The corporation is also investing in developing new writers and new producers with projects including Jesting About </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">which aims to uncover co</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">medy talent. One of the successes of that project is North East writer-performer Jason Cook whose BBC2 comedy Hebburn is into i</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ts second series. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Executives at BBC North are currently</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in discussions with Northern Film and Media and other partners about brin</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ging further projects to the region.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Without the BBC, the North East television production sector would now be a shadow of its former self. It is the view of myself and many others in the region, that the BBC used its influence and resources to positively</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> make a difference to a </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">production sector and programme-making tradition which had found itself facing terminal decline. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Seven years ago, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">London-based </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ITV, Channel 4, Five and Sky were unable to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">offer the North East production se</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ctor a lifeline. The BBC </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">however recognized the value of making use of experienced production teams and location managers. And further realized the positive impact on audiences of making television from this region of England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">This seems sensible and strategic </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">use of the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> licence </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">fee </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">- which </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">of course </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">partly made up of contributions from the two million people resident in households around North East England.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>